## 🚀 Kubernetes Pod Autoscaling

### 1. Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA)
* **Concept:** Increases or decreases the number of **replicas** (Pods) based on observed metrics [01:29](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=89).
* **Mechanism:** Runs as a controller in the control plane. It periodically queries the **Metrics API** [01:47](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=107).
* **Requirements:** * A **Metrics Server** must be installed (default in GKE, manual in EKS) [02:15](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=135).
    * Pods **must** have defined `resource requests` [03:37](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=217).
* **Interview Tip:** HPA uses *requests*, not *limits*, to calculate utilization percentages. Avoid setting `replicas` in your deployment YAML if using HPA to prevent "flapping" with GitOps tools like ArgoCD [04:50](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=290).

### 2. Vertical Pod Autoscaler (VPA)
* **Concept:** Adjusts the **CPU and memory reservations** (vertical scale) of existing Pods rather than adding more Pods [07:48](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=468).
* **Modes:**
    * **Off (Recommendation):** Only provides suggestions; doesn't change anything (safest for production) [08:29](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=509).
    * **Initial:** Assigns resources only at Pod creation.
    * **Recreate:** Evicts and restarts Pods to apply new limits (risky for stateful apps) [08:06](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=486).
* **Critical Rule:** Never use HPA and VPA on the same metrics for the same workload; they will conflict [08:59](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=539).

### 3. KEDA (Kubernetes Event-Driven Autoscaling)
* **Concept:** Scales workloads based on **external events** (e.g., message queue depth, database queries) [10:14](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=614).
* **Unique Feature:** Can **scale to zero** if there are no events, saving significant costs [10:36](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=636).
* **Use Case:** Ideal for ETL pipelines or microservices reacting to Kafka, RabbitMQ, or AWS SQS [11:14](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=674).

