## 🏗️ Kubernetes Node (Cluster) Autoscaling

### 1. Cluster Autoscaler (CA)
* **Mechanism:** Watches for **Pending Pods** that cannot be scheduled due to lack of resources [12:36](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=756).
* **Scaling:** Increases the size of Cloud Provider **Node Groups** (ASGs).
* **Limitation:** It usually scales by adding identical nodes from a pre-defined group, which can lead to wasted resources if a small Pod triggers a large node creation [12:50](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=770).

### 2. Karpenter
* **Concept:** A more flexible, high-performance autoscaler (originally by AWS) [13:14](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=794).
* **Mechanism:** Bypasses Node Groups. It evaluates the specific requirements of pending Pods and provisions the **exact instance type** needed (Just-in-time provisioning) [13:23](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=803).
* **Benefit:** Faster and more cost-efficient than CA by reducing resource "slack" [13:38](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=818).

### 3. Serverless (Fargate / Autopilot)
* **Concept:** Removes the need to manage nodes entirely [13:58](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=838).
* **Mechanism:** The cloud provider provisions a dedicated, right-sized compute environment for every Pod [14:06](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=846).
* **Trade-off:** Higher cost per unit of CPU/RAM but significantly lower operational overhead [14:13](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsJ2qtwoWZw&t=853).

